Seed Point Correlation Method Demo¶

This script will show the usage of factory 'OI_Functions\Seed_Grid' Base on already read-in Raw R value matrix. Spatial Filter and blk concat etc shall be done before. If you bin, it also need to be done before the usage.

Ver 0.24.07.1 'Squid'

Before use, you need to get **raw R value (NOT dR/R)** matrix of graph,in shape(N_frame,height,width) You might also need to set a save folder, all results will be saved here.

Okay, then we will do bin for this data, as 20Hz is way too quick and have high noise.

We use bin=4, after this, the data shall be in 5Hz.

In [ ]:
binsize = 4

fps = 20/binsize # 4 binned 20Hz is 5Hz

binnum = frames.shape[0]//4 # ignore unfinished part
raw_R_frame = np.reshape(frames[:binnum*binsize,:,:],(binnum,binsize,frames.shape[1],frames.shape[2])).mean(1)

print(f'Size After Bin is:{raw_R_frame.shape}')

Size After Bin is:(7545, 256, 256)

Here Comes the important part¶

Step1:Set the factory¶

You will have to define:

  • Input R value frame
  • fps of frame capture
  • size of grid, you need to set each grids' pixel size
  • save folder
In [ ]:
save_folder = r'D:\YJX\spon_data\240719_RF_OIS_TEST\Run02_RF_VBar_20Hz_2ms\Preprocessed\Seed_Tests'
# define class parameter
SCG = Seed_Correlation_Grid(frame=raw_R_frame,fps = fps,grid_size=8,save_folder=save_folder)

# you can real length of frame anytime by calling len(SCG)
print(f'Total input frame num:{len(SCG)}')
# you can get each single frame by given the id of it.
print(f'Single Frame Shape:{SCG[0].shape}')

Total input frame num:7545
Single Frame Shape:(256, 256)

Step2, cut gragh and define dR/R method.¶

Use function SCG.Grid_Cutter() to get grid response. Para explained below:

  • clip: Clip of average graph, change visual effect only.
  • font_size: size of grid annotation font. For different grid size, you need to change it to see number clearly.
  • drr_method: IMPORTANT. We provide 2 way of getting dR/R. If it's set 'before', dR/R will be done on each pixel's time course, and add each grids' tc together; else if it's set 'after', we will add up all pixels in each grid, then do dR/R. As you can see, 'before' is always slower.
  • save: bool. If set True, save gridded dR/R in savepath.

Grid dR/R will give you a cutted demo, you can choose seed through it.

In [ ]:
# para here are default paras. If you use default, no need to assign them agian, just run 'SCG.Grid_Cutter()'
SCG.Grid_Cutter(clip=2,font_size=10,drr_method = 'after',save = True)

Step3, set seed coordinates¶

After evaluation, you need to decide which point(or points are seeds), just put coordinate of seed grid(s) into function'SCG.Seed_Determine()'

IMPORTANT: Coordinates of seed grid shall be given in seq Y,X. and the seed must be given through a list, each element is a set of id.

In [ ]:
seed_coords = [(4,9),(4,10),(5,10)]
SCG.Seed_Determine(seed_coords)

Seed Number:3

Step4, generate correlation matrix¶

IMPORTANT: This step must be done after seed selection. Easy why.

Parameters:

  • corr: Method of correlation.'Pearson' for pearson R and 'Spearman' for spearman R.
  • HP & LP: High-pass and Low-pass filter of data. You can set it as False to skip.

After this operation, the correlation matrix is saved in SCG.Seed_Corr; P value of each compare are in SCG.Seed_Corr_p

In [ ]:
# here we use default parameter.
SCG.Correlate_Grids('Pearson',HP = False,LP = False)

# plot correlation matrix toward seed point.
corr_mat = SCG.Seed_Corr
sig_mat = SCG.Seed_Corr_p
sns.heatmap(corr_mat,center = 0,square=True)

Step4 (Ver.b), Slide-window seed correlation.¶

If you think the correlation might change through time, we provide you a slide-window method in function 'SCG.Correlate_Grid_Slide_Window()' You need to set the window length and window step. Both need to be given in Seconds

The result is saved in 'SCG.Seed_Corr_Win' and 'SCG.Seed_Corr_Win_p'.Both is a 3D matrix, in seq(win_number,grid_vertical,grid_horizontal)

In [ ]:
SCG.Correlate_Grid_Slide_Window(win_len = 90,win_step = 30,LP=False,HP=False)

corr_win_mat = SCG.Seed_Corr_Win
sig_win_mat = SCG.Seed_Corr_Win_p

print(f'Shape of slide window correlation:{corr_win_mat.shape}')

# and we show an example corr frame.
sns.heatmap(SCG.Seed_Corr_Win[0,:,:],center = 0,square=True)

Save all slided windows in save path.

In [ ]:
# make subfolder
slide_path = cf.join(save_folder,'Slide_Window_Corrs')
cf.mkdir(slide_path)


# cycle time window.
vmax = 1
vmin = -0.8
for i in tqdm(range(len(SCG.Seed_Corr_Win))):
    c_graph = SCG.Seed_Corr_Win[i,:,:]
    plt.clf()
    plt.cla()
    fig,ax = plt.subplots(ncols=1,nrows=1,figsize = (5,5),dpi = 240)
    sns.heatmap(c_graph,xticklabels=False,yticklabels=False,square=True,ax = ax,center=0,vmax = vmax,vmin = vmin)
    fig.savefig(cf.join(slide_path,f'{10000+i}.png'))
    plt.close(fig)
